{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525038"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:11:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:11:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14052"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14052"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.23,0.05,0.07,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52886"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6706"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43928"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52886"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of abdominal pain. While the pain initially started in her lower back, over the last three days she has developed severe nausea, vomiting, and right upper quadrant pain. She has felt increasingly confused over the past 24 hours. She has a medical history of anorexia nervosa and depression. Her only regular medication is sertraline, and she has additionally been taking regular ibuprofen and paracetamol since her pain commenced. She drinks four to six standard drinks on weekends and smokes cannabis fortnightly, but does not smoke tobacco or use any other recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears thin and unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. She is jaundiced and drowsy, frequently falling asleep during review and requiring rousing. She has a non-distended abdomen with right upper quadrant tenderness without hepatomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 1100 U/L (5-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 900 U/L (5-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP: 250 U/L (30-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT: 380 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin: 120 \u03bcmol/L (3-17)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 28 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 2.0 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 150 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute cholecystitis","Acute cholangitis","Liver cirrhosis","Alcoholic hepatitis","Acute liver failure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and laboratory findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute liver failure\u003C/strong\u003E. Acute liver failure is defined as the development of coagulopathy (INR \u22651.5) and any degree of encephalopathy within 26 weeks of the first symptoms in a patient without pre-existing liver disease. This patient presents with confusion (suggesting encephalopathy), coagulopathy (INR 2.0), and markedly elevated liver enzymes, all of which have developed rapidly over a few days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in the setting of chronic alcohol abuse and usually presents with a more indolent course. The AST:ALT ratio is typically \u0026gt;2:1 in alcoholic hepatitis, which is not the case here. Additionally, the patient\u0027s reported alcohol use does not suggest chronic abuse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver cirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition characterized by long-term liver damage and scarring. While it can lead to similar laboratory abnormalities, the acute onset of symptoms and rapid progression to encephalopathy are more consistent with acute liver failure rather than cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the gallbladder and typically presents with right upper quadrant pain, fever, and leukocytosis. While this patient has right upper quadrant pain, the severe liver function abnormalities and encephalopathy are not typical of acute cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an infection of the biliary system that can cause right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, and fever. While biliary obstruction can sometimes lead to transaminitis, the presence of encephalopathy and synthetic liver dysfunction would not be explained by this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of acute liver failure in developed countries is paracetamol toxicity, which should be considered in this case given the patient\u0027s reported use. Patients who are underweight are at greater risk of paracetamol toxicity at lower ingestion levels. Other potential causes include other drug-induced liver injury, viral hepatitis, and Wilson\u0027s disease. Regardless of the underlying cause, the priority in management is to recognize the acute liver failure, provide supportive care, identify and treat the underlying cause if possible, and evaluate for potential liver transplantation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute liver failure is characterized by the development of coagulopathy and encephalopathy in a patient without pre-existing liver disease.","Paracetamol toxicity is the most common cause of acute liver failure in developed countries.","Prompt recognition and management of acute liver failure is crucial, as it can rapidly progress to multi-organ failure."],"references":["Cordoba J, Dhawan A, Larsen FS, Manns M, Samuel D, Simpson KJ, et al. EASL Clinical Practical Guidelines on the management of acute (fulminant) liver failure. J Hepatol. 2017 May;66(5):1047-1081. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28417882/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14052"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-11T11:41:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T11:43:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6706"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52886"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"